<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat, Rabin, Peres, Mandela, De Klerk Praised </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat, Rabin, Peres, Mandela, De Klerk Praised </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904190294 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2904190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The talks started more than five months ago in 
Paris. Today, Israel and the PLO signed an agreement laying the 
framework for economic relations between the Jewish state and 
the self-governing territories under Palestinian control. Trade 
tariffs, the currency to be used, and taxation policy were at 
the center of the talks. Here is Foreign Minister Alain Juppe, 
who welcomed both delegations this morning: 
  [Begin Juppe recording] There will be obstacles on the road 
to peace, there were in the past. All those who prefer war to 
peace will attempt to derail this process. There were 
horrendous attacks on both sides, however the process continues. 
Those who chose peace with great courage and with a sense of 
responsibility and statesmanship will win, and they deserve 
admiration, I mean Yitzhaq Rabin, Shim'on Peres, Yasir 'Arafat, 
and all his team. 
  International affairs bring us their daily share of 
disasters, from time to time there is an international event to 
cheer us up. There was the Oslo agreement on 13 September last 
year, now there are elections in South Africa, a country that I 
visited two or three months ago. I was also impressed by the 
role played by two outstanding men, Nelson Mandela and President 
de Klerk. Despite the attacks, I am convinced that these men 
and this people have such strength that the future of South 
Africa can be contemplated with optimism. This is France's 
belief and France will lend its support. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

