<H3> <TI>   Helios II Satellite Approved </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Helios II Satellite Approved </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2904144294 Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES in French 27 Apr 94 
p 11 </F>

<F P=103> BR2904144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Leotard Decides To Launch Helios II </F>
Satellites"] 
  [Text] Defense Minister Francois Leotard recently decided 
to implement the definition phase of the Helios II military 
ground observation satellite program, which, for the time being, 
is solely French. Compared with Helios I (two optical 
observation satellites, one of which will be put into orbit at 
the start of 1995), the Helios II program will develop 
higher-capacity satellites which will use infrared technology to 
see at night as well as during the day and even in bad weather 
conditions. They are due to enter service in the year 2001. 
The overall program will cost 10 billion francs [Fr] (for two 
satellites), including Fr770 million for the definition phase. 
The Helios I program, run jointly with Italy (14 percent) and 
Spain (7 percent), had been estimated at almost Fr8 billion. 
The Helios II program initially provides for the launch of a 
satellite in 1999, 2001, 2004, and 2006. 

</TEXT>

