<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papandreou `Satisfied' With U.S. Trip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papandreou `Satisfied' With U.S. Trip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2904191594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1805 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2904191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou returned satisfied 
from his trip to the United States. In a statement shortly 
before leaving New York for Athens, Papandreou said that his 
trip had specific goals that have been partially achieved. He 
added that some issues will be evaluated later. 
  Asked whether his expectations from the visit were 
fulfilled, 
Papandreou said: I cannot say that the flow of history has 
changed. In any case, we managed to make our positions 
understood and interlocutors were responsive. 
  Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias described as completely 
unfounded rumors that he had met with Stevo Crvenkovski, his 
counterpart from Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM], adding that he is ready to return to New 
York if talks on Skopje require it. 

</TEXT>

