<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Oil Exploration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Oil Exploration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3004155794 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1450 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA3004155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, April 30 (AA) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin on Saturday [30 April] said that in frame of previous 
agreements, Turkey will join in oil exploration projects in 
Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan. 
  He told reporters upon his arrival at Ankara's Esenboga 
Airport following a visit to these countries that the Turkish 
Petroleum Company (TPAO) will be participating in the project, 
adding Turkmenistan is at the moment producing 5.5 million 
tonnes of oil yearly. 
  Answering reporters' questions, Cetin expressed belief in 
the 
advantage on the continuation of talks process for finding a 
solution to the Cyprus problem. 
  On the embargo imposed to Iraq, he said that Iraq is 
complying by the embargo rules, adding the United Nations 
Security Council also is expecting this country to take positive 
steps on the issue of Kuwait's independence and territorial 
borders. 
  On Bosnia-Herzegovina, he underlined the importance of 
bringing to a stop Serbian offensive, stressing that this would 
not necessarily mean that the conflict has been solved. 
  "What matters is the independence and sovereignty of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. If a real cease-fire is reached, such a 
process can start." He said. 
  Cetin also expressed belief that a continuation of UN-NATO 
cooperation is vital to at least set up safe areas where 
necessary. 

</TEXT>

