<H3> <TI>   Government Reportedly Disagrees on Arms Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Reportedly Disagrees on Arms Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205130994 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 2 May 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Pressure of Industry"] </F>
  [Text] In a secret meeting this week, the Federal Security 
Council will decide on the principles of German arms exports. 
Preparatory talks between Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, 
Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt, and Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel were unsuccessful, state secretary in the Economics 
Ministry Reinhard Goehner (Christian Democratic Union -- CDU) 
told CDU members. According to Goehner, above all, Foreign 
Minister Kinkel has objections. The foreign minister fears that 
Bonn's restrictive guidelines on arms exports, which were 
adopted in 1982, could be undermined by a more liberal 
cooperation arrangement of German firms with foreign companies. 
However, in the Economics Ministry and the Bundestag group of 
Christian Democrats and the Christian Social Union [CSU] the 
readiness is growing to yield to the pressure of the German arms 
industry, which argues by referring to jobs and the possible use 
of military know-how for civilian purposes. 

</TEXT>

