<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Trends Show `Positive Economic Growth' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Trends Show `Positive Economic Growth' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205181194 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 2 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "West German Economic Situation </F>
Undergoes Broad Improvement"] 
  [Text] For the first time in 20 months, the HANDELSBLATT 
economic trend indicator for May suggests positive economic 
growth. It also reveals a 0.2 percent improvement against April. 
In April, the indicator displayed a 0.1 percent fall in 
economic growth, a decrease of 0.3 points. Compared with May 
1993, economic growth was 1.4 points higher. 
  This latest development permits the conclusion that the west 
German economy has overcome the recession and will embark upon a 
path of growth in the summer. If the positive trend of the past 
few months continues, a 1.5 percent increase in the GNP should 
be achieved in 1994. 
  May also appears a good month regarding the extent of the 
signs of improvement. All six individual growth figures given 
in the indicator have improved, most of them considerably. 
  The structure of interest rates has again normalized 
following an uninterrupted fall since December 1990. In March, 
capital market interest rates were 0.36 percent points higher 
than short-term rates for three-month money deposits. 
  After boosting exports in previous months, the positive 
economic signals now seem to be boosting domestic demand. In 
February, the processing industry registered a 2.3 percent 
increase in demand against January. 
  In January, the construction industry enjoyed a veritable 
leap in demand as orders increased by over 10 percent compared 
with December, which in itself was quite a good month. 
  Retail trade turnover, always a reliable indicator of 
private 
consumption in recent months, in February saw a 1-percent growth 
against January. 
  In the meantime, the traffic lights of exports have settled 
on green. In February, foreign orders for the processing 
industries increased by 3.8 percent against January. 
  The Institute for Economic Research's exports surveys for 
enterprises are becoming increasingly optimistic. In March, the 
number of enterprises expecting further improvement over the 
next three months leapt from 14.2 percent in February to 15.6 
percent. The business climate in the processing industry also 
improved from minus 18.7 percent in February to minus 12.5 
percent in March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

