<H3> <TI>   Greek, Albanian Ministers in Zurich May Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greek, Albanian Ministers in Zurich May Hold Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0305141694 Bern ATSA/SDAA Database in French 1155 GMT 03 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0305141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA Database </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed MA/BL/NB: "Greek-Albanian meeting in Zurich </F>
-- Development and Content of Talks Still Uncertain"] 
  [Text] The meeting between the Greek and Albanian foreign 
ministers is expected to take place. Greek Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias arrived at Zurich-Kloten Airport from Athens 
on Tuesday [3 May] morning. His Albanian counterpart Alfred 
Serreqi had arrived in Zurich on Monday evening. 
  The holding of the talks and the issues to be discussed were 
still uncertain on Tuesday morning. The Greek Embassy is 
referring all requests for information to the Foreign Ministry 
in Athens. The meeting was proposed two weeks ago in Greece 
after a border incident triggered a political crisis. 
  On 13 April, three days after the fatal attack against a 
border Albanian military camp by Greek nationalists, Albania 
expelled four Greek diplomats from Tirana. Greece reacted by 
evicting an Albanian diplomat. New skirmishes broke out over 
the weekend between Greece and Albania on the occasion of the 
Orthodox Easter celebrations. 
  Greece threatened to cancel the Zurich meeting. On Sunday, 
Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou hinted that the talks 
might take place anyway. On Monday evening, around 1,000 
Albanians demonstrated in front of the Greek Consulate. They 
denounced the "aggressions against Albanians" and pleaded for a 
return to peace in the Balkans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

