<H3> <TI>   Major Supports Issuing of Identity Cards </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Major Supports Issuing of Identity Cards </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904090294 London THE GUARDIAN in English 29 Apr 94 p 
10--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PM2904090294 </F>
<F P=104>  London THE GUARDIAN </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Stephen Bates article: "Major Supports Call for ID Cards"] </F>
  [Text] The Prime Minister appeared to give his support 
yesterday to the introduction of identity cards for all 
citizens. 
  He told MPs during question time there was a strong case for 
identity cards despite practical difficulties, and said they 
were being considered. 
  The Government has previously always concluded that the 
practical difficulties and cost of issuing accurate and 
up-to-date identity cards made it impractical, though they are 
popular with the otherwise libertarian right as a means of 
tracking criminals and preventing social security fraud. 
  Any attempt to introduce identity cards would cause 
political 
controversy and opposition on civil liberties grounds. 
  The issue was raised by the right-wing backbench MP Nicholas 
Budgen (Wolverhampton SW) in the wake of police swoops on 60 
alleged illegal immigrants from Africa working for 
Labour-controlled Southwark council. 
  Mr Major said: "I think there is a strong case to be made 
for 
identity cards. There are undoubtedly great practical 
difficulties in introducing them, and there are other matters to 
be considered as well, but we have been looking at the options 
in this respect and we propose to go on doing so." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

