<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO's Woerner Criticizes Debate Over Bundeswehr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO's Woerner Criticizes Debate Over Bundeswehr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804192694 Hamburg DPA in German 1830 GMT 28 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner has 
sharply criticized the current discussion about the Bundeswehr 
in Germany. The German armed forces have increasingly turned 
into a "quantity that is negotiable at short notice," he stated 
today in Bonn during the presentation of a book by Bundeswehr 
Inspector General Klaus Naumann. "If this development 
continues, we will be facing problems," he pointed out. 
  Woerner criticized that the strength and the structure of 
the 
Bundeswehr seem to be "manipulable at will." This cannot be 
blamed on the defense minister alone. The whole government and 
the whole parliament are responsible. Woerner added: "If the 
impression is created among the public that one can treat the 
Bundeswehr in this way, this is the beginning of the end of 
sensible security precaution in Germany." Yet not the soldiers 
are to blame but the entire political class. 
  The NATO secretary general stressed that the reunited and 
sovereign Germany can only remain a reliable partner if, as the 
central land power in Europe, it maintains armed forces that 
correspond to its geostrategic situation and its political 
significance -- both in quantitative and qualitative terms. At 
the beginning of his speech, Woerner pointed out that, as NATO 
general secretary, he is not allowed to interfere with the 
internal affairs of the member states of the alliance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

