<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Bosnian Serbs Framed Workers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says Bosnian Serbs Framed Workers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205162794 Paris AFP in English 1611 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, May 2 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb officials plan to 
try at least three French aid workers Sunday [8 May] on charges 
of smuggling weapons to Moslem forces, the relief organization 
Premiere Urgence said. 
  Eleven members of the emergency aid group have been held at 
a 
Bosnian Serb barracks near Sarajevo since April 8. 
  The organization issued a statement saying the Serbs "seem 
to 
have refrained from judging all 11 of Premiere Urgence's 
volunteers in order to bring charges against three members of 
the team." 
  The organisation strenuously denied Serb charges that it had 
channeled arms to Bosnian Moslem forces. 
  The group said it believed the other eight volunteers could 
be released before their colleagues go on trial. 
  France recently demanded the immediate and unconditional 
release of all 11 aid workers. French Foreign Minister Alain 
Juppe has said he believes they have been framed by the Serbs. 
  Several observers, including lawyers and also 
representatives 
of the International Federation of Human Rights and Amnesty 
International, hope to make their way on Friday to the Bosnian 
Serb headquarters at Pale, outside Sarajevo, where the three 
workers are to stand trial, Premiere Urgence added. 

</TEXT>

