<H3> <TI>   SPD Executive Committee Adopts Government Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Executive Committee Adopts Government Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205171194 Hamburg DPA in German 1620 GMT 2 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0205171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- After a four-hour debate, the Social 
Democratic Party of Germany's [SPD] executive committee 
unanimously adopted the draft government program on Monday [2 
May] with only one abstention, SPD Chairman Rudolf Scharping 
told the press afterwards. Following a comprehensive debate, 
various items were added to the part on ecology, but the 
controversial wording of the speed limit has remained unaltered. 
  The passage says that the SPD is aiming at a universal speed 
limit throughout Europe, which would be 130 kilometers per hour 
for 90 percent of all super highways, Scharping said. 
  The SPD chairman said that there was no criticism of his 
leadership -- "quite the contrary." The withdrawal of traffic 
expert Christoph Zoepel from his team was only mentioned 
briefly, [Scharping said]. 

</TEXT>

