<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi's Three Government Guarantors Profiled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi's Three Government Guarantors Profiled </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2904113394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2039 GMT 28 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2904113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bios of Berlusconi's Three `Wise </F>
Men'"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Rome, April 28 -- Antonio La Pergola, 
Giorgio Crisci and Agostino Gambino are the three "wise men" 
that Premier-designate Silvio Berlusconi today named to act as 
guarantors that his business interests in no way conflict with 
his public office. 
  La Pergola, who was born in Catania, Sicily, on November 13, 
1931, was president of the Constitutional Court from July 2, 
1986 to June 14, 1987 and community policies minister in the De 
Mita and Goria governments. On March 25, 1994, the outgoing 
Ciampi government named him as the 13th judge on the European 
Court of Justice. In addition to teaching constitutional law at 
the universities of Padua, Bologna and Rome, La Pergola has also 
been a member of the Council of Magistrates. In 1989 he was 
elected to the European Parliament. 
  Crisci, born in Rome on January 23, 1923, is a lawyer and 
president of the Council of State. He has served as president 
of TAR [Regional Administrative Tribunal] in Sicily and as a 
juridical advisor and cabinet chief in various ministries. He 
is the author of numerous judicial studies. 
  Gambino was born in Genoa on July 6, 1933 and is a professor 
of commercial law at the La Sapienza University of Rome. He has 
served on a panel made up of representatives of the government 
and the Holy See to oversee relations between the Vatican Bank 
(IOR) and the Banco Ambrosiano and on a panel the government 
formed in July 1992 to oversee the liquidation of Federconsorzi. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

