<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Discusses Privatizations, Monetary Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciampi Discusses Privatizations, Monetary Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2904140894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1239 GMT 29 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2904140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi on Privatization and Lira"] </F>
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 29 -- The ongoing process of 
privatization in Italy is "a reality in continual evolution and 
it is right that it be debated upon even for the general rules 
for joint stock companies" outgoing Italian premier Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi said here Friday [29 April] at a press conference 
called to review his year in office. 
  The former bank of Italy governor went on to state that he 
had no intention of getting involved in the polemics, 
highlighted in the press, over the recent privatization of Comit 
[Italian Commercial Bank]. 
  However, in answer to charges that Banca Commerciale 
Italiano 
had been taken over by a small "hard-core" of stockholders, 
Ciampi recalled how while 20 percent of shareholders had, 
indeed, organized, "there always remains 80 percent of 
shareholders which can organize and find the ways and means to 
do so. 
  Turning his attention to monetary matters, Premier Ciampi 
expressed his hope that the lira would return to the European 
Monetary System (EMS) as quickly as possible. 
  "In 1992" he recalled, "the EMS suffered a crisis much worse 
than that of the lira" adding how for "national pride 
adjustments had not previously been made to parities which would 
have avoided the increase in rates." 
  Looking at the independence of the Bank of Italy Ciampi 
stated how in his fourteen years at the head of the central bank 
he had always fought to boost its independence which was 
achieved "starting in 1981 when the Bank of Italy was no longer 
obliged to purchase unsold state paper put up for auction and 
ended with its freedom to set the discount rate." 

</TEXT>

