<H3> <TI>   Investments Expected To Rise in 1995 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investments Expected To Rise in 1995 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0305105294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1411 GMT 30 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0305105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Investment To Rise in 1995, ISCO </F>
Says"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 30 -- Investment will flourish in 
1995, after remaining fairly stable overall in 1994, according 
to a report from the short-term economic trends study institute 
ISCO [National Institute for the Study of the Economic 
Situation], released Saturday [30 April]. 
  This year will see a rise in the amounts ploughed back into 
medium-sized companies for investment purposes but small and 
large industry will continue to languish, pushing the overall 
figure down by about 1.9 percent, said ISCO in its six-month 
report. 
  This figure is fairly healthy when compared with the 13.5 
percent drop chalked up in 1993, said ISCO, adding that the 
average fall in investments last year across the European Union 
stood at around 12 percent. 
  An ISCO poll showed that two-thirds of companies questioned 
said that they planned to step up investments next year, with 
large-sized firms leading the field. 

</TEXT>

