Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2904103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Three Parties Forced Into Single </F>
Parliamentary Caucus"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 28 -- Three smaller parties that 
do not have enough seats in the Lower House to form separate 
groups will be forced to join a single so-called mixed group 
because the speaker's office on Thursday [28 April] turned down 
their applications to form separate ones. 
  The Socialist and Democratic Alliance parties each have 15 
Lower House deputies while the Pact for Italy has 13, all below 
the 20-member floor limit for the formation of a separate group 
under the current rules. 
  The three parties ran separately in the March elections (in 
some constituencies with the progressives) and are not keen to 
be forced into a single caucus and risk being seen by public 
opinion as interchangeable. 

</TEXT>

