<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Delegation Returns From Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Delegation Returns From Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0205162394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1500 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0205162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, May 2 (A.A.) -- A delegation including the 
General Staff and Foreign Ministry officials returned to Turkey 
after completing official contacts with UN Protection Forces 
(UNPROFOR) officials. 
  General Staff spokesman Colonel Dogu Silahcioglu said the 
delegation met Croatian officials on April 28 and UN officials 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina to set up a date for the deployment of 
Turkish troops to Bosnia. 
  Silahcioglu said the Turkish delegation and UN officials 
reached an understanding on the structure of Turkish soldiers, 
their necessities and location where they will function. 
  Turkish troops will include a mechanized infantry battalion 
and military engineering and logistics team including health and 
transport personnel to support this battalion. 
  He said all necessary preparations were completed for the 
active functioning of Turkish soldiers. 
  Following a request from the United Nations, Turkey has 
agreed to send a 2,700 military personnel. 
  UN officials said the infantry comprising 1,000 people is 
expected to be set up between Bosnians and Croatian forces in 
the buffer zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

