<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "G-7, Aid to Russia at Hata-Ciampi </F>
Talks"] 
  [Text] Rome, May 3 (ANSA) -- The July summit of the seven 
major industrialized countries and economic aid to the former 
Soviet republics, and to Russia in particular, were the two main 
points discussed at a meeting here Tuesday [3 May] between 
Japanese Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata and caretaker Prime 
Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, a government communique said. 
  Hata, the communique said, confirmed Japan's full support of 
the approach given by the Italian chairmanship of the G-7 
summit, to take place in Naples July 8-10, which will issue two 
separate economic and political statements as well as a 
"declaration" on security summing up talks held at the summit 
with Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  Ciampi today reiterated his suggestion that the 
International 
Monetary Fund issue special drawing rights to support economic 
reforms in the former Soviet Union. 
  The two government heads also discussed the situation in 
China, the communique said. 
  After his meeting with Ciampi, the Japanese premier attended 
a working lunch with industrial leaders including Fiat Chairman 
Gianni Agnelli, Alitalia Chairman Renato Riverso and ENI 
[National Hydrocarbons Agency] Managing Director Franco Bernabe. 

</TEXT>

