<H3> <TI>   Kohl Discusses Search for Peace in Bosnia at Vatican </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Discusses Search for Peace in Bosnia at Vatican </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305135094 Hamburg DPA in German 1220 GMT 3 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0305135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome (DPA) -- The talks conducted by Federal 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl with Cardinal State Secretary Angelo 
Sodano in The Vatican on Tuesday [3 May] focussed on 
possibilities for cooperation in the search for a peaceful 
solution for Bosnia-Herzegovina. Other issues discussed in the 
meeting with the "head of government" of the church state were 
the enlargement of the European Union, and the role of United 
Nations in international hotspots, Vatican Spokesman Joaquin 
Navarro-Valls said. Bilateral issues, such as the relationship 
between the church and state in the FRG were also broached. 
  Kohl, who is due to return to Bonn on Tuesday night, asked 
Sodano to convey to Pope John Paul II his best wishes for 
recovery on behalf of the Federal Government. Originally, the 
chancellor was scheduled to meet the pope, but the private 
audience had to be canceled due to the church leader's hip 
operation on Friday. 
  Upon his arrival in Rome on Monday night, Kohl paid tribute 
to John Paul's role in the reshaping of Europe. The pope made 
"an essential contribution to overcoming totalitarianism and the 
division of Germany and Europe," Kohl said at a reception in the 
German Embassy in the Vatican. 

</TEXT>

