<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Election Results: New Government Undecided </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Results: New Government Undecided </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405095294 Hilversum Radio Netherlands in English 0830 GMT 
4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hilversum Radio Netherlands </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Here in the Netherlands the current coalition 
government of Christian Democrats and Social Democrats has lost 
its majority in parliament after yesterday's parliamentary 
elections. 
  The Christian Democrats, the CDA, received more than 35 
percent of the vote in the 1989 general election, but they have 
now slumped to just over 22 percent. The Social Democrats 
[PvdA] also lost ground. Their share of the votes fell from 32 
percent to 24 percent, but they emerged as the largest party in 
the new Dutch parliament. The two major opposition parties -- 
the Conservative Liberal VVD, and the Progressive Liberal D66 -- 
made significant gains in the elections. Both now have a 
significant number of seats in parliament. The remaining seats 
were won by a total of eight smaller parties. 
  The results provide no firm indication of the composition of 
the new government. It is clear, though, that any new coalition 
government will need the backing of at least three parties to 
secure a parliamentary majority. 

</TEXT>

