<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amsterdam, Colombo To Discuss Tamils Repatriation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amsterdam, Colombo To Discuss Tamils Repatriation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0305135394 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 3 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR0305135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Netherlands To Discuss Repatriation </F>
of Tamils With Sri Lanka"] 
  [Text] The Netherlands is to discuss with Sri Lanka the 
possible repatriation of Tamils residing in the Netherlands. 
One and a half weeks ago, the Foreign Ministry asked its 
representative in Colombo to start discussions on the subject 
with the authorities in Sri Lanka. 
  This move was a response by the Foreign Ministry to a 
request 
by Netherlands State Secretary for Justice Kosto. The Justice 
Ministry believes the discussions should lead to an agreement in 
principle on the return of the Tamils, in the manner of similar 
agreements concluded with Sri Lanka by Switzerland and India. 
  If the Netherlands and Sri Lanka are able to reach such an 
agreement, the repatriation will take place under UNHCR [United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees] supervision. The 
Justice Ministry believes that some 20,000 Tamils are living in 
the Netherlands. The size of the group which would be liable 
for compulsory repatriation is not known. 
  Civil war is still waging in the north of Sri Lanka where 
armed Tamils are fighting for their own state. The Foreign 
Ministry considers the south and center of the country to be 
"safe." "The internal refugee situation has improved," a 
Justice Ministry spokesman reported. The Netherlands has 
previously concluded a repatriation agreement with Vietnam. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

