<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Warns Against Making Islam `New Enemy' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Warns Against Making Islam `New Enemy' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0405124794 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
4 May 94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> AU0405124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Foreign Minister Warns of New Enemy </F>
Image"] 
  [Text] Mannheim, 3 May -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
and his Dutch counterpart Pieter Kooijmanns have warned against 
building up the image of Islam as the new enemy in Europe after 
the end of the East-West antagonism. At the first 
German-Netherlands ambassadors' conference in Mannheim on 
Tuesday [3 May], the two officials came out in favor of 
conducting a frank and critical dialogue with the Islamic states 
and promoting mutual understanding by getting to know one 
another better. 
  The German and Netherlands ambassadors to Algeria, Egypt, 
Saudi Arabia, Iran, and Turkey participated in the conference. 
The exchange of opinions focused on questions of stability in 
the southern Mediterranean region and in the Middle East. 
  Kooijmans said that Islam was in many cases equated with 
extremism and fundamentalism. While extremism was dangerous, it 
was not immediately connected with Islam. There were fanatics 
in other religions too, Kooijmans stated, adding that the 
Europeans should not be guided by fear of the Islamic world. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

