<H3> <TI>   Rules Out Higher Taxes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rules Out Higher Taxes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0405104394 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 4 May 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU0405104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["deu"-signed report: "SPD Does Not Want To Increase Taxes"] </F>
  [Excerpt] Bonn -- Rudolf Scharping, chairman of the Social 
Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] and candidate for chancellor, 
has confirmed his promise that, as chancellor, he will not 
increase the quota of taxes and surcharges beyond the level 
planned for 1995. "This is a very clear promise," Scharping 
stated in Bonn on Tuesday [3 May] after the session of the SPD 
Party Council, which was harmonious, according to participants 
in the meeting. The body that includes representatives of the 
land and district organizations discussed the draft of the 
government program that was adopted by the SPD Executive 
Committee one week ago with one abstention. Scharping added that 
even unpleasant surprises when counting the cash after a 
changeover of power in Bonn would not change anything. The limit 
of burdens has been reached. Within the existing system, 
however, he considers a number of changes necessary. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

