4 May 94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> AU0405124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["J.K."-initialed report: "Several Thousand Jobs To Go at </F>
Opel"] 
  [Excerpt] Frankfurt/Main -- Opel will cut another several 
thousand jobs. According to information received from the 
German subsidiary of the U.S. automobile group General Motors, 
the management and the work council are currently talking "about 
necessary measures to adapt the size of the work force to 
requirements." In the enterprise, which has 47,600 employees, 
the work force will be reduced by some 2,000 men and women 
"beyond natural fluctuation for structural reasons by the end of 
the year." In plain English this means that twice as many jobs 
as the figure that was mentioned are to be cut as part of 
streamlining measures. After all, with a company of the size of 
Opel, "natural fluctuation" should involve about 2,000 people a 
year. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

