<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Hata Begins European Tour </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Hata Begins European Tour </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305013694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0116 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305013694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, May 2 KYODO -- Japan's new Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata arrived in Rome on Monday [2 May] night, kicking 
off a series of official visits to Italy, France, Germany and 
Belgium. 
  Hata's trip, which comes less than a week after he became 
prime minister, is intended to forge personal ties with European 
leaders ahead of the July summit in Naples, Italy, of the Group 
of Seven (G- 7) major industrialized nations, Foreign Ministry 
officials said. 
  In Rome, Hata will hold talks Tuesday with Italy's outgoing 
Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi and Prime Minister-designate 
Silvio Berlusconi. Italy currently chairs the G-7 process. 
  On a flight from Tokyo, Hata told reporters Japan wants to 
strengthen relations with Italy and other members of the 
European Union. 
  A planned meeting with Pope John Paul II was canceled due to 
the pope's leg injury. 
  The trip was originally scheduled for January by then Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, but was postponed due to the 
volatile domestic political scene. 

</TEXT>

