<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Scalfaro </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets With Scalfaro </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0305125694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1248 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0305125694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, May 3 KYODO -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata told Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro on 
Tuesday [3 May] that Tokyo wants to strengthen and expand its 
ties with Europe. 
  Hata told Scalfaro that Japan needs to make important 
contributions to the international community, and hopes to 
promote cooperation with European nations knowledgeable and 
experienced in affairs in Africa, the Middle East and East 
Europe. 
  During the 45-minute meeting, the Italian head of state 
asked 
about the future prospect of economic relations between Japan 
and the United States, the world's two largest economic powers, 
saying the relationship will affect many other countries. 
  The prime minister expressed hope to settle a bilateral 
impasse over trade "framework" talks at an early date, the 
officials said. 
  Hata assured Scalfaro that the outcome of talks between 
Japan 
and the United States will apply to any other country. 
  Hata's predecessor, Morihiro Hosokawa, and President Bill 
Clinton failed in their February summit in Washington to strike 
a deal on a new framework to slash Japan's trade surplus and 
increase its share of imports. Talks have not been resumed. 
  Hata arrived in Rome Monday night, kicking off a series of 
official visits to Italy, France, Germany and Belgium. 
  Hata's trip, less than a week into his post as prime 
minister, is aimed at forging personal ties with leaders before 
the July summit of he Group of Seven (G-7) major industrialized 
nations, in Naples, Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

