<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Berlusconi, Ciampi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets With Berlusconi, Ciampi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0405021394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0204 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0405021394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, May 4 KYODO -- Japanese Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata pledged to Italian Prime Minister-Designate Silvio 
Berlusconi Tuesday [3 May] night that Japan will continue to 
make efforts to open up its market, Japanese officials said. 
  "A little brightness has been visible in the Japanese 
economy. We are making efforts to make Japan's market open to 
the international community," Hata was quoted as saying. 
  The Japanese prime minister said he wants to deepen 
exchanges 
with Italy in politics, the economy, science and culture, the 
officials said. 
  During a 45-minute meeting, Berlusconi replied that his 
country also shares similar problems and when he assumes the 
post of prime minister, Italy's economy will be strengthened and 
it can make a fresh start, the officials said. 
  Berlusconi, appointed prime minister-designate last week, 
said he is looking forward to working with Hata at the July 
summit of the Group of Seven (G-7) major economic powers in 
Naples. 
  Earlier in the day, Hata met departing Prime Minister 
Azeglio 
Ciampi for two and a half hours. 
  Hata and Ciampi agreed that strengthening cooperation on 
political problems between Russia and the G-7, revitalization of 
the world economy, and assistance to African countries and other 
developing nations will top the agenda at the Naples summit, the 
officials said. 
  Ciampi said, "in the summit meeting, we would like to 
discuss 
strengthening cooperation on political issues between the G-7 
and Russia. We also want to discuss relations between North and 
South, and assistance to developing nations." 
  Hata reportedly replied that summit meetings of the G-7 will 
assume new importance in a new era and praised Italy's role. 
  The Japanese prime minister said it is important to extend 
aid to developing countries, and Middle East and East Europe. 
  Hata, who was elected prime minister last Monday, arrived in 
Rome on Monday night, kicking off a series of official visits to 
Italy, France, Germany and Belgium. 
  Hata's trip is aimed at forging personal ties with leaders 
before the July summit of the G-7. 

</TEXT>

