<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Papoulias-Serreqi Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Papoulias-Serreqi Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0305163194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0305163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias and 
Albanian Foreign Minister Alfred Serreqi described their meeting 
in Zurich today as positive. Papoulias said that Albania showed 
signs of goodwill but he stressed that many problems remain 
unsolved. 
  Papoulias stressed the issue of five Greeks being held by 
Albanian authorities, an issue that Serreqi said is in the hands 
of Albanian justice. 
  Serreqi raised the issue of the Tsamidhes [Muslims living in 
Greece south of the Albanian border drawn at the end of WWII and 
who assisted the communists during the Greek civil war] but 
Papoulias replied that Greece considers them to be war criminals. 
  The meeting also discussed the latest border incident at 
Episkopi, which the Albanian foreign minister described as a 
terrorist act. 
  [Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek at 1500 GMT on 3 
May 
carries a related recorded report from Zurich. Correspondent 
Foivos Karzis notes that "a first step toward normalizing 
Greek-Albanian relations, a step mainly directed at changing the 
climate between the two countries, since no specific commitments 
were made, was taken today in Zurich with the meeting between 
the two foreign ministers, Karolos Papoulias and Alfred Serreqi. 
In substance, this meeting reexamined the whole topic of 
bilateral relations. A positive point to emerge from the 
meeting is that Tirana appears to recognize the importance of 
having good relations with Athens. But the distrust between the 
two countries is widespread and Papoulias' hesitation shows the 
Greek side's reservations." 
  [Papoulias is then cited as saying: "Goodwill was 
ascertained 
today at the negotiating table but it should be turned into 
practice. There are many unsolved problems in Greek-Albanian 
relations."] 

</TEXT>

