<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brussels Demands Formal Apology From Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Brussels Demands Formal Apology From Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0305134994 Brussels LE SOIR in French 30 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BR0305134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LE SOIR </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed Th.F.: "Brussels Demands Formal Apology From </F>
Rwanda"] 
  [Excerpt] Belgium has given its first official response to 
the Rwandan accusations that Belgium was involved in the attack 
on 6 April in Kigali which cost the life of President 
Habyarimana and led to the massacres. Yesterday morning, 
Francois Ngarukiyintwali, the Rwandan ambassador in Brussels, 
was called to the Foreign Ministry. After announcing Belgium's 
"vigorous" protests at the statements made by the Rwandan 
ambassador in Zaire, in particular, and by the Rwandan foreign 
minister, the Foreign Ministry's Secretary General Roelants 
repeated that Belgium had nothing to do with this tragedy, 
either through the Belgian units which are part of UNAMIR (UN 
Mission in Rwanda) or through any Belgian authority. 
  Consequently, the Rwandan ambassador was informed that the 
Belgian Government is demanding the interim Rwandan Government 
to formally and unequivocally withdraw the statements that 
Belgium was an accomplice, an instigator, or the perpetrator of 
the assassination of Juvenal Habyarimana, as well as the 
statements claiming that the Rwandan Patriotic Front (FPR) 
received support from Brussels. 
  As long as these statements have not been withdrawn, neither 
the Rwandan foreign minister nor any member of the interim 
Rwandan Government will be allowed into Belgium. This does not 
mean a breakdown in diplomatic relations between Brussels and 
Kigali. To put it plainly, any future contact between Belgium 
and Rwanda at the highest level will be subject to an apology 
from Rwanda. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

