<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Wants `Urgent' Meeting on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Wants `Urgent' Meeting on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305171794 Paris AFP in English 1643 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0305171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, May 3 (AFP) -- France and the United States 
agreed Tuesday [3 May] on the urgent need to organize a 
ministerial meeting on Bosnia due to the recent spread of 
fighting, French Foreign Ministry spokesman Richard Duque said. 
  French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher agreed on the move during a telephone 
conversation Tuesday morning, he said, giving no details of 
where or when such a meeting might take place. 
  He said an urgent meeting is needed in particular because of 
the increased threat of conflict outside the six UN-designated 
safe areas in Bosnia-Hercegovina. 
  "The prevention of new slippages...necessitates the 
deployment on the ground of new protection forces outside the 
security zones established by the UN Security Council." 
  He said a switch from "respecting Security Council 
resolutions to Atlantic Alliance decisions" was required, in an 
apparent reference to the possibility of using force. 
  Concern has been focussed in recent days on the Brcko 
corridor in northeastern Bosnia, where Serbs are trying to widen 
their supply route between Serbia and northwest Bosnia. 
  Duque said there was "a worrying concentration of troops 
from 
both sides" in the region, adding that talks were continuing on 
a possible increase in peacekeeping forces, in particular around 
Brcko. 
  Military analysts predict that Brcko, in a five-kilometre 
(three-mile) bottleneck in supply-lines from Serbia to Serb 
areas in northwestern Bosnia, will be the next target of Serb 
offensive. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

