<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Departs for PLO-Israel Signing Ceremony </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin Departs for PLO-Israel Signing Ceremony </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0405104194 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 0700 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0405104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has stated that steps 
are being taken toward a new Middle East -- politically, 
economically, and socially -- and added that Turkey will 
continue to contribute in that direction. Cetin departed for 
Egypt to participate as an observer in the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement signing ceremony in Cairo. 
  In a predeparture statement at Ankara's Esenboga Airport, 
Cetin said that the agreement is a historic turning point with 
regard to formulating the structure of Palestinian self-rule in 
Gaza and Jericho. Pointing out that peace is a process which 
needs time and patience, Cetin explained that there have been 
difficulties since the Declaration of Principles agreement was 
signed in Washington. Stressing that peace-loving countries in 
the region made great efforts, Cetin added: 
  [Begin Cetin recording] The personal contributions of 
Egypt's -- friend and brother Egypt's -- President Husni Mubarak 
expedited the signing of the agreement. Turkey, from the start, 
contributed to the Middle East peace process and stated that 
only by negotiations and dialogue can peace be achieved in the 
Middle East. Within this framework, Turkey participated in all 
the multilateral meetings -- five working groups -- and 
perpetuated its contributions toward the peace process. 
  From the beginning, Turkey supported the five working groups 
and was an active participant in these multilateral meetings. 
As a matter of fact, Turkey used its historical, brotherly, and 
cultural relations with the Arab world and its good relations 
with Israel, as the only Muslim country which recognized it from 
the beginning, positively. Turkey always used its relations 
with Israel and with brotherly and friendly Arab countries 
toward peace. The point reached today is historical. [end 
recording] 
  Expressing great happiness at being able to participate as 
an 
observer at such an important agreement, Cetin said that Turkey 
will continue to contribute to the peace process in the 
restructured Middle East. 
  Cetin will return to Turkey after the Gaza-Jericho agreement 
signing ceremony. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

