<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Journalists Protest `Police Brutality' on May Day </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Journalists Protest `Police Brutality' on May Day </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0305153094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1505 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0305153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, May 2 (A.A.) -- The Turkish Journalists' 
Union released a written statement on Monday [2 May] deploring 
the police brutality that occurred during Sunday's May Day 
demonstrations. 
  The statement said taking the film cassettes and hindering 
television cameramen were direct obstruction of press 
organizations. 
  The statement also said these incidents were not only 
attacks 
on journalists but at the same time limitations of the right to 
receiving news. 
  Social Democratic Populist Party (SHP) deputy Salman Kaya 
was 
beaten by police during Sunday's May Day demonstrations. 
  In Ankara a demonstration by the `democratic platform' which 
was organized by Turk-Is, DISK and Hak-Is unions, started 
quietly at noon, but failed to end the same way when a group of 
demonstrators refused to disperse afterward. Their refusals 
triggered a clash during which the demonstrators divided into 
two groups. One group started stoning cars. A man who fell 
over the Sihhiye bridge during the clash with the police and who 
was taken to hospital is not in critical condition. 
  Officials said a number of people have been detained for 
`provocation of the people'. 
  May Day was celebrated by various rallies in Turkey as `the 
day for international unity, solidarity and struggle.' 
  Economic rather that political slogans were spoken during 
the 
rallies. 
  The leaders of the Turkish Confederation of Trade Unions 
(Turk-Is), the Confederation of Revolutionary Trade Unions 
(DISK) and the Hak-Is confederation united under the democratic 
platform in Istanbul. 
  Together with the three confederations, the syndicates of 
public employees and democratic mass organizations also held 
rallies in Izmir, Adana, Bursa, and Samsun. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

