<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nordic Countries Plan Defense Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nordic Countries Plan Defense Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305172894 Stockholm Radio Sweden in English 1615 GMT 3 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sweden, Norway, Denmark, and Finland plan to 
cooperate in the production and purchase of arms in order to cut 
defense costs and ensure the survival of their respective 
national arms industries. 
  Nordic defense ministers meeting in Denmark today expect a 
preliminary agreement on arms cooperation will be signed at 
their next meeting in Sweden in June. 
  Norway and Denmark are members of the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization, NATO, while Sweden and Finland are neutral. Close 
defense cooperation between the four would have been unthinkable 
only a few years ago. But the end of the Cold War, Sweden and 
Finland's agreement to join NATO's Partnership for Peace 
program, and Sweden, Norway, and Finland's applications to join 
Denmark in the European Union, have paved the way for them to 
extend the traditionally close Nordic cooperation in most areas 
to the defense sector as well. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

