<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Netherlands' Lubbers Seeks EC Presidency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Netherlands' Lubbers Seeks EC Presidency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0405073094 Paris AFP in English 2122 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0405073094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Hague, May 3 (AFP) -- Outgoing Dutch Premier 
Ruud Lubbers will stand as a candidate to succeed Jacques Delors 
of France as president of the European Commission, the Foreign 
Ministry said Tuesday [3 May]. 
  Foreign Minister Pieter Kooijmans will formally present 
Lubbers' candidacy to the European Union soon, the Ministry said 
in a statement. 
  Lubbers resigned earlier Tuesday as general elections were 
held in the Netherlands. He was not running for re-election. 
  Until now Lubbers, 55 in a few days, had refused to say if 
he 
was aiming for Delors' job, saying to discuss it would be 
inappropriate as long as he was head of the Dutch government. 
  Delors' term expires on January 5 of next year. 
  In 1992 the Frenchman said Lubbers would be a good 
successor, 
and Dutch television said Tuesday it was Delors himself who 
encouraged Lubbers to seek the post. 
  Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene, a Christian 
Democrat 
like Lubbers, is also seeking the job and diplomats say he has 
the support of France and Germany. 
  Lubbers has led three coalition governments in the 
Netherlands over the past 12 years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

